player.seasonOutlook: Reagor was on the field for 67% of the Eagles' snaps and posted a 31-396-1 receiving line in 11 games as a rookie in 2020. He played 67% of the snaps and posted a 33-299-2 receiving line in 17 games in 2021. Needless to say, that's not what Philadelphia was hoping for when they selected Reagor in the first round of the 2020 draft. His efficiency has been atrocious (his 0.8 YPRR was dead-last and 5.2 YPT 89th among 91 qualified WRs in 2021) and his playing time is sure to dip with A.J. Brown and Zach Pascal added to a WR room that also includes DeVonta Smith. Reagor is only 23, but a breakout season as a depth receiver in Philadelphia's run-heavy scheme is a long shot. He's only worth rostering in dynasty.

Pascal reunited with former coordinator and current Eagles head coach Nick Sirianni when he signed with the Eagles in the offseason. Pascal was busier than you probably realize during his time with the Colts. He was on the field for 78% of the snaps and handled 14% of the targets during the 2019-21 campaigns. Primarily a short-to-midrange target, Pascal has struggled to put up big yardage and TD numbers (career highs are 629 yards and five TDs). He has never had a top-50 fantasy campaign and was among the 10 worst wide receivers in catch rate (54%), yards per target (5.5) and YPRR (0.8) last season. Pascal will compete with Jalen Reagor and Quez Watkins for work behind A.J. Brown and DeVonta Smith. The 27-year-old remains a long shot for fantasy value.

Rodgers is entering his second NFL season after being limited to 99 snaps in 12 games as a rookie. He was targeted eight times and added an 11-yard rush while being utilized in the short area (4.8 aDOT). The latter is far from a surprise considering his skill set and RB-like build, not to mention his 6.4 aDOT at Clemson during the 2018-20 seasons. Most second-year, early-round picks are promoted to a larger role, and Rodgers at least has a shot for more work after the departures of Davante Adams and Marquez Valdes-Scantling. Rodgers' top competition for targets is the likes of Allen Lazard, Sammy Watkins, 32-year-old Randall Cobb and rookies Christian Watson and Romeo Doubs. Consider Rodgers with a late pick in deeper leagues.

Callaway exited 2020 as a relative unknown after going undrafted earlier that year and barely seeing the field as a rookie. A strong showing during the 2021 offseason, coupled with injuries to Michael Thomas and Tre'Quan Smith, and Callaway was suddenly New Orleans' No. 1 wide receiver. He averaged 15.2 yards per reception (12th highest) in his role as a vertical target, but he simply wasn't very productive or consistent. Even with six touchdowns on the board, Callaway finished 43rd in fantasy points. The 24-year-old is a strong bet for a step back this season with substantially more competition for targets in the form of Thomas, Jarvis Landry and first-round pick Chris Olave. Callaway is best left on waivers.

Nailor was selected by Minnesota in the sixth round of April's draft. Nailor is an explosive receiver who never played more than nine games in a single season at MSU due to injuries. Nailor dealt with poor QB accuracy during his time at MSU, as a class-low 60% of his targets were catchable (no one else was below 68%), which somewhat excuses a class-low 49% catch rate. He'll need to cut down on drops and the durability is obviously a major issue, but Nailor's quickness and post-catch ability (career 8.2 RAC) make him an intriguing WR/returner prospect. He'll compete for a backup gig in Minnesota.

Heyward was selected by Pittsburgh in the sixth round of April's draft. He is listed as a tight end, but he's 233 pounds (lightest in this rookie TE class) and is more of a fullback/H-Back prospect. Cameron's little brother racked up 208 carries during his four seasons at Michigan State, but had only one in his new role in 2021. His 1.6 career aDOT (3.8 in 2021) confirms his short-area usage and his pro role is unlikely to allow any fantasy upside, especially with Pat Freiermuth atop the TE depth chart in Pittsburgh.

Washington selected Brown is the third round of the 2021 draft and immediately inserted him into a starting role opposite Terry McLaurin. It didn't last long. Brown turned 20 targets into 81 yards during his first five games and then was sent to the bench. He was limited to 84 yards on five targets the rest of the season. Brown was primarily utilized as a vertical target (14.8 aDOT) and was able to haul in only 12 of his 25 targets. He is only 22 years old and Washington's QB situation is improved with Carson Wentz under center, but he's suddenly fourth on the depth chart behind Terry McLaurin, first-round rookie Jahan Dotson and a healthy Curtis Samuel. Brown is best as a stash in dynasty.

Ferguson was selected by Dallas in the fourth round of April's draft. Ferguson was a busy man during four seasons at Wisconsin, having racked up 205 targets on a class-high 2,574 snaps. His career 18% target share is also highest in this rookie TE class and he was at or above 19% in three of the four seasons. Ferguson was a consistent factor in the passing game despite spending a ton of time run blocking (56% of his snaps). Ferguson is oldest among the top rookie TEs and posted low-end showings in hand size, wingspan, 40-yard dash and bench press at the combine. Ferguson will slot in a situational player behind Dalton Schultz in 2022.

Gray was selected by the 49ers in the third round of April's draft. He caught 69 balls during the 2018-19 seasons at Blinn Junior College before transferring to SMU in 2020. Gray posted a solid 82-1,251-13 receiving line during two campaigns at SMU, handling an 18% target share when active. His career 9.0 RAC is best in this year's rookie class. He's on the thin side and had drop issues (7.4% rate), but he ran a strong 4.33 40-yard dash at the combine and looks like a capable depth receiver and returner. He'll battle with Jauan Jennings and Ray-Ray McCloud for No. 3 duties behind Deebo Samuel and Brandon Aiyuk and should be drafted only in dynasty leagues.

The Chargers drafted McKitty in the third round of the 2021 draft. He spent most of his rookie campaign behind Jared Cook and Donald Parham, which allowed him only eight targets on 228 snaps, 45 of which were pass routes. McKitty is an obvious candidate for a bigger role as a Day 2 pick in his second season, though his path to fantasy value is cloudy with Parham and new projected starter Gerald Everett in the mix. McKitty was a rarely targeted, short-range option in college and seems a long way off from fantasy value. He's worth considering only in deep dynasty formats.

Ebner was selected by Chicago in the sixth round of April's draft. Ebner was best as a receiving back and returner during his four seasons at Baylor, totaling 1,574 yards and seven TDs on 320 carries, 1,248 yards and eight scores on 134 targets and 1,318 yards and four TDs on 71 returns. Ebner's career rushing efficiency isn't impressive (he lost yards on 25% of carries, 2.6 YAC), but his overall elusiveness sure is (one forced missed tackle for every 2.9 touches for his career is best in class). Ebner also averaged a strong 9.3 yards per target for his career. Ebner has the speed (4.43 40-yard dash) and versatility to emerge as a passing-down/return specialist in the pros. He'll battle Khalil Herbert for No. 2 duties behind David Montgomery.

Williams was selected by the Rams in the fifth round of April's draft. Williams is undersized, but he's tough and able to align all over the field while contributing as a rusher, receiver and blocker. We saw that in play during his time at Notre Dame, as he reached 200 carries, 35 receptions and 14 TDs each of the last two seasons. Williams impressed after contact (3.6 YAC) and in terms of tackle breaking and elusiveness, but his 4.65 40-yard dash at the combine (83 speed score) is about as poor as it gets for a sub-200-pound back. He also checked in with short arms and was also shaky in the vertical and broad jump. Perhaps Williams will emerge as a Theo Riddick/Dion Lewis type, but that's likely his ceiling.

Quitoriano was selected by the Houston in the fifth round of April's draft. Quitoriano is a blocking tight end who was targeted a grand total of 54 times on 1,648 snaps during four seasons at Oregon State. He blocked on a class-high 79% of his snaps and even pass blocked on a massive 52% of the pass plays he was on the field for. Quitoriano's career 4% target share allowed a 40-512-6 receiving line. He's big and athletic, but he has the smallest hands in the class and the collegiate usage suggests he's unlikely to be a receiving threat in the pros.

Ezukanma was selected by Miami in the fourth round of April's draft. He is a tall, long-armed, perimeter prospect who racked up at least 65 targets as a starter at Texas Tech each of the last three seasons. He ended up with a 138-2,165-15 career receiving line, which was fueled by target and air-yard shares above 20% in each of his final two seasons. He aligned in the slot on 9.7% of his career routes (lowest in this rookie class) and will need to clean up the drops a bit (career 6.2% drop rate). Ezukanma will open his career as a depth receiver behind, at least, Tyreek Hill, Jaylen Waddle and Cedrick Wilson. He should only be rostered in dynasty.
